'''Gateshead International Stadium''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose]], [[all-seater]] arena in [[Felling, Tyne and Wear|Felling]], [[Tyne and Wear]], England. Originally known as the '''Gateshead Youth Stadium''', the venue was built in 1955 at a cost of <U+00A3>30,000. It has since been extensively re-developed on three occasions. Its capacity of around 11,800{{refn|group=nb|This is the most widely quoted figure, but at least one council document provides a figure of 11,750.<ref name="Quinn">{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-23427/Item+09+-+Delivery+of+the+Redevelopment+of+Gateshead+International+Stadium+report.doc |title=Report to Cabinet &ndash; Delivery of the Redevelopment of Gateshead International Stadium|first=Derek |last=Quinn |publisher=Gateshead MBC |date=27 January 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.3</ref>}} is the greatest in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Gateshead]], the third-largest in Tyne and Wear (behind only [[St James' Park]] and the [[Stadium of Light]]) and the sixth-largest in [[North East England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstadiums.com/europe/countries/united_kingdom/england/north_east.shtml|title=Stadiums in North East England|publisher=World Stadiums|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>

The main arena is principally used for [[Athletics (sport)|athletics]]. The inaugural athletics competition at the redeveloped venue, the 1974 "Gateshead Games", was instigated by [[Brendan Foster]], a Gateshead Council employee at that time. By breaking the world record in the [[3000 metres|mens 3,000&nbsp;m]], Foster brought international publicity to the new stadium and began a tradition of athletics competitions at the venue, which has since hosted the [[British Grand Prix (athletics)|British Grand Prix]] (2003&ndash;10) and the [[European Team Championships]] in 1989 and 2000. The stadium was selected to host the latter event for a third time<U+2014>the only venue to have done so<U+2014>in 2013. Five world records have been set at the stadium, including two by [[pole vault]]er [[Yelena Isinbayeva]] and a tied [[100 metres]] record by [[Asafa Powell]] in 2006.

Although the venue primarily caters for athletics, it is currently home to teams in several sports. [[Gateshead F.C.|Gateshead football club]] have played their home games at the stadium since they reformed in 1974 though the club plans to vacate the site when their [[Gateshead F.C. new stadium|own purpose-built ground]] is built. Gateshead International Stadium was home to the [[Gateshead Thunder]] [[rugby league]] club during their spell in the [[Super League]] and the current version of the club play home games in the main arena, which is known as the '''Thunderdome''' when used by that team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gateshead Thunder end two-and-a-half year wait for win|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-league/19422254|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> Gateshead Harriers Athletic Club, which includes Foster and [[Jonathan Edwards (athlete)|Jonathan Edwards]] among its life members, are the oldest tenants, having used the site since 1956. The stadium has been used as a concert venue by numerous musical artists including [[Bon Jovi]], [[Bryan Adams]] and [[Tina Turner]].

==History and development==

During the 19th&nbsp;century, Felling became an important industrial town in the north east of England. At its north-western fringe, at Felling Shore, two large chemical works opened in 1827 and 1834.<ref name="chroniclelive1">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/communities/felling/2012/01/01/ten-interesting-facts-about-felling-72703-30939585/|title=Ten interesting facts about Felling|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=1 January 2012|accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref><ref>Lewis, 1848: 227</ref> These initially thrived, but by the early part of the 20th century both were in terminal decline,<ref>Hewitt (part three), 1990: 1 at para. 5</ref> and were demolished in 1932 to leave behind a 2-million-tonne heap of spoil.<ref name="chroniclelive1"/><ref name="powell8">Powell, 2010: 8</ref> This land, approximately {{convert|2|mi}} east of the centre of Gateshead,<ref>Powell, 2010: 7</ref> was cleared in 1942 but continued to lie derelict until the mid-1950s.<ref name="powell8"/>

In early 1955, Gateshead Council began work on transforming this land. The Gateshead Youth Stadium, built on the site of the old chemical works, was opened by [[Jim Peters (athlete)|Jim Peters]] on 27 August 1955.<ref name="gateshead1">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead2013.com/thevenue.html|title=The Venue &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2013|accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref> Costing <U+00A3>30,000, the original venue contained little more than a cinder running track and an asphalt cycling track, though floodlights and a seating area were added soon after.<ref name="gateshead1"/> On 1 July 1961, the arena hosted its first major competition<U+2014>the [[Vaux Breweries]] International Athletics Meet<ref name="BGR">''The Brewing Grade Review'', 1961: 922</ref><U+2014>but according to sportswriter John Gibson, the Youth Stadium remained "little more than a minor track with a tiny grandstand and open terraces".<ref name="ICN">{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html|title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster|first=John|last=Gibson|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2004|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.2</ref>

[[File:Gateshead 1975.jpg|thumb|Aerial photograph of Gateshead and Felling (1975). The rebuilt stadium is prominent (top centre).]]According to author Thomas Telfer, by the turn of the 1970s, the town of Gateshead was suffering from "the classic symptoms of decay in its inner-city areas". The response during the 1960s had been a programme of systematic derelict land reclamation and environmental improvement.<ref>Telford, 1988: 79</ref> While these measures did not have an immediate positive impact on the perception of the town, Gateshead Council pressed ahead by looking to develop existing infrastructure with a view to overall regeneration.<ref>Telford, 1988: 80</ref> One such opportunity was identified at the Gateshead Youth Stadium, where the council believed that investment might raise the region's profile and bring international recognition.<ref>Moore, Fox and Elliot, 2003: 107</ref> In April 1974, Gateshead Council inaugurated a "Sport and Recreation" department.<ref name="ICN"/> In July 1974, the council appointed [[Brendan Foster]]<U+2014>a former schoolteacher turned athlete and a native of [[Tyne and Wear]]<U+2014>as the Council's sport and recreation manager.<ref name="Gibson 2004:1"/><ref name="Freedom">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/3761364.stm|title=Foster given Freedom of Gateshead|publisher=the BBC|date=20 October 2004|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> Foster, who according to Gibson became "the father of Gateshead athletics",<ref name="Gibson 2004:1">{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html|title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster|first=John|last=Gibson|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2004|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> had been forced to train in [[Edinburgh]] during 1973 as a result of the poor condition of the Youth Stadium track.<ref name="UKA">{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/e-inspire/hall-of-fame-athletes/brendan-foster/|title=Brendan Foster|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|year=2011|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> In December 1973, he had been invited to a civic reception to celebrate his breaking of the two-mile world record earlier that year at Crystal Palace. At this reception, Foster was told that a new [[all-weather running track|synthetic track]] was being laid at Gateshead Youth Stadium. His response was a promise that, if the Council was serious, he would run at the stadium and break a world record (Foster later offered an explanation of that promise: "You know how it is when you've had a few drinks&mdash;you promise the world!").<ref name="ICN"/> When the track was laid in early&nbsp;1974, Foster became convinced of the Council's sincerity.<ref name="ICN"/> He was interviewed for the managerial position<ref name="ICN"/> and, upon appointment, became the "driving force"<ref name="Freedom"/> behind the programme of improvements to the Youth Stadium, which included the building of the main, covered Tyne and Wear stand in 1981<ref name="blue"/> and three accompanying stands; the venue was renamed the Gateshead International Stadium.<ref name="gateshead1"/><ref name="Freedom"/> This first tranche of improvements cost around <U+00A3>8&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/domesday/dblock/GB-424000-561000/page/2|title=Domesday Reloaded: Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|year=2011|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> and Foster's proposal to commemorate the re-opening with an athletic event was approved, allowing for the first "Gateshead Games" to be held in 1974.<ref name="Gibson 2004:1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1090986/2/index.htm|title=Howay, Big Bren! Ye're doin' us prood!|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|first=Ray|last=Kennedy|date=19 April 1976|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Gateshead stadium.jpg|thumb|The Tyne and Wear Stand]]The success of the first Gateshead Games, and their subsequent annual renewal, raised the profile of the stadium and caused Gateshead Council to further their financial investment. During the 1980s, additions were made to the site infrastructure, including the building of an indoor sports hall, outdoor football pitches and a gymnasium.<ref name="gateshead1"/> In 1989 the running track was again relayed<ref name="TrackDir"/> and Gateshead confirmed its reputation as a top-class athletics venue by hosting the [[European Cup (athletics)|Europa Cup]] (forerunner to the [[European Team Championships]]).<ref name="Europa1">{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/3007647/Athletics-Gateshead-glory-had-invigorating-effect.html|title=Gateshead glory had invigorating effect|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=Knight|first=Tom|date=20 June 2001|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> In the 21st century, the site has been the subject of two major re-development projects. The first was completed in 2006, when two artificial outdoor football pitches, indoor athletic training facilities, sports science provisions and conferencing rooms were added at a cost of <U+00A3>15&nbsp;million.<ref name="pitch up">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/PITCH%20UP%20AT%20GATESHEAD%20INTERNATIONAL%20STADIUM.aspx|title=Pitch up at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|date=27 June 2006|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> The revamped stadium, funded by collaboration between [[One NorthEast]], [[Sport England]] and [[Gateshead College]] among others, was opened on 12 May 2006 by [[Sebastian Coe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/Lord%20Coe%20Opens%20New%20Development%20at%20Gateshead%20International%20Stadium.aspx|title=Lord Coe opens new development at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|date=12 May 2006|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref>

A second tranche of development, undertaken in two stages, was approved in November 2009.<ref name="Richards">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2009/11/04/plans-to-revamp-gateshead-stadium-unveiled-72703-25089463/|title=Plans to revamp Gateshead Stadium unveiled |first=Linda|last=Richards|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 November 2009|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> This included a general refurbishment and improvement of the existing facilities at the stadium, adding cover, better toilet and new refreshment facilities to the exposed East Stand, improving wheelchair access, adding extra catering and conferencing facilities and a new media and management centre.<ref name="ALee">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/news/development/GIS.aspx|title=Development Plans: Gateshead International Stadium|first=A|last=Lee|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2010|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref name="DB5">{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26070/Item+15a+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief.pdf|title=Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief|author=Powell|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.5</ref> This was funded by collaboration between Gateshead Council, local development funds and Gateshead College.<ref name="ALee"/> The covering of the 4,000-seat<ref name="Richards"/> East Stand with a new canopy roof<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-27570/Item+06+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+-+Tender+report.doc|title=Report to cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Main Arena Tender|first=Dowling|last=Paul|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=20 July 2010|accessdate= 28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> was completed in July 2010, immediately prior to Gateshead hosting a [[2010 IAAF Diamond League|Diamond League]] event.<ref name="covered">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/GatesheadInternationalStadiumimprovements.aspx|title=Gateshead International Stadium Improvements; Spectators to be covered in glory in time for sprinting champions head to head |publisher=Gateshead Council|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> The second stage of the re-development<U+2014>the building of the corporate and media facilities<U+2014>commenced on 6 September 2010 and was completed on time in summer&nbsp;2011.<ref name="ALee"/> The total cost of the work was estimated to be <U+00A3>7.6&nbsp;million.<ref name="DB5"/>

A third programme of expansion was initially mooted in 2008. The aim of this programme was to expand the stadium into an all-embracing "sports village",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26070/Item+15a+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief.pdf|title=Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief|author=Powell|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.3</ref> replete with an ice rink, indoor golf course, restaurants and shops. Gateshead Council invited tenders in August 2008 from commercial organisations interested in undertaking the development.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/7579943.stm|title=Ice arena plan at sports stadium|publisher=BBC|date=24 August 2008|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> A formal draft development brief was compiled and published in November 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26070/Item+15a+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief.pdf|title=Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief|author=Powell|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref> A report to Council in December 2009 noted that there had been "a reasonable level of interest at the preliminary stage" from private investors, but that only one detailed proposal had been submitted, which had been declined by the Council on financial grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> The report also noted concerns that the original centrepiece of the proposed village, the ice rink, may have been deterring investors and that a similar proposal to redevelop land at the [[Stadium of Light]] in [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] was detracting from what councillors had hoped to be a unique feature of the proposed village.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.7</ref> The result was that a fresh proposal was raised to remove the ice rink from the brief in an attempt to "stimulate the market".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.8</ref> A public consultation was undertaken and in May 2010 the council reported that 327 of the 375 responses received were in favour of the amended proposal.<ref name="Dowling">{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-27194/Item+10+-1-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Development+Brief+report.doc|title=Report to cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Development Brief|first=Dowling|last=Paul|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> As a result, notice was given to developers that the council intended to market the site and ten responses were received.<ref name="Dowling"/>

==Structure and facilities==

[[File:Gateshead International Stadium Layout.png|thumb|Diagram demonstrating layout of main arena at Gateshead International Stadium<ref name="UKA Aviva"/>]]Gateshead International Stadium and its facilities occupy {{convert|24.4|ha|acre}} of land.<ref>Powell, 2010: 7 at para.17</ref> The main athletics arena at Gateshead International Stadium is an [[All-seater stadium|all-seater]], bowl-shaped arena consisting of four stands of seats.<ref name="blue">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluesqfootball.com/story/0,20970,13036_3770978,00.html|title=Gateshead|publisher=Bluesquarefootball.com|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> The precise capacity of the venue is uncertain; some sources claim it to be 11,750,<ref name="Quinn"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/gateshead-international-stadium|title=Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> others 11,762<ref name="TrackDir"/> and some provide a figure of 11,800.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=970|title=Gateshead International Stadium&nbsp;- Home of Thunder|publisher=[[Gateshead Thunder]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/4125/media-watch-grounds-for-hope-over-new-gateshead-fc-stadium|title=Media Watch &ndash; Grounds for hope over new Gateshead FC stadium|first=Steve|last=Brown|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|date=23 August 2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> The main stand is the Tyne and Wear Stand, a steep, [[cantilever]]ed structure<ref name="blue"/> seating 3,300 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2487/fa-cup-gateshead-v-brentford-saturday-7th-november-match-information|title=FA Cup: Gateshead v Brentford &nbsp;- Saturday 7th November &nbsp;- Match Information|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|date=4 November 2009|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> This stand contains toilet and catering facilities and a bar area.<ref name="blue"/> Opposite is the East Stand, a 4,000-seat structure that was uncovered until 2010, when a cantilevered [[Canopy (building)|canopy]] roof was added. A bespoke design by Fabric Architecture, the roof is a {{convert|30|m|ft}} structure incorporating five [[barrel vault]] forms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cms.esi.info/Media/documents/80083_1308047032870.pdf|title=Fabric architecture Ltd&nbsp;- Case study: Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Fabric Architecture|year=2009|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> Part of the same improvement plan added toilet and catering facilities to the East Stand.<ref name="covered"/> The South Terrace, sometimes referred to as simply the South Stand,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/07/17/queen-to-visit-gateshead-and-newcastle-tomorrow-72703-31410354/|title=Replay our blog from the Queen's visit to Tyneside|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=18 July 2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> consists of a continuous, uncovered bank of seating in eight blocks with access through four [[turnstiles]].<ref name="UKA Aviva">{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/training-zone/2010/aviva-british-grand-prix/|title=Aviva British Grand Prix|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=10 July 2010|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> The North Terrace is opposite and consists of two blocks of uncovered seating separated by a large scoreboard.<ref name="UKA Aviva"/>

The athletics track in the main arena was laid in 2003 and is an [[International Association of Athletics Federations]] (IAAF) standard 400m eight-lane oval. It is a polymer synthetic [[tartan track]] with a depth of {{convert|3|cm|in|2}}. The sprint straight consists of eight lanes and is situated in front of the Tyne and Wear Stand, adjacent to the [[long jump|long]] and [[triple jump]] area. A height-adjustable water jump, for use in [[Steeplechase (athletics)|steeplechase racing]], is located on the inside of the track.<ref name="TrackDir"/><ref name="UKA Aviva"/><ref name="MBCfacts">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/facilities/GIS/home.aspx|title=Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> [[Floodlights (sport)|Floodlights]] allow athletics events to be held at night.<ref name="TrackDir"/> The inner track area, which is floodlit, is an IAAF standard-sized grass surface used for athletics field events, rugby and football.<ref name="MBCfacts"/> When used for the latter, the pitch dimensions are {{convert|100|x|64|m|yd|1}}.<ref name="blue"/>

The main arena is supplemented by other facilities. To the rear of the North Terrace are two [[Artificial turf|third generation artificial]] pitches that are [[UEFA]] licensed, fully floodlit and full-sized for use in competitive rugby, football and American football.<ref name="pitch up"/> Alongside them are two grassed and one sand-dressed playing areas, which are also floodlit.<ref name="pitch up"/><ref name="MBCfacts"/> Behind the Tyne and Wear Stand is an indoor sports hall, which contains a {{convert|33|x|44|m|yd|1}} playing area marked out for various sports including badminton, netball and tennis.<ref name="MBCfacts"/> A retractable indoor athletics facility was previously housed alongside the sports hall, consisting of a {{convert|50|m|yd}} long synthetic sprint straight and areas for throwing and jumping events, but its mechanical operation proved problematic<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.runtrackdir.com/details.asp?track=gateshead-s-indoor|title=Gateshead International Stadium Indoor Track|publisher=Running Track Directory|first=Tim|last=Grose|date=30 May 1999|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> and a more modern structure replaced it in 2006. This facility has a {{convert|60|m|yd}} sprint straight in an {{convert|82|m|yd}} hall, throwing and jumping facilities, a weights room and gymnasium.<ref name="MBCfacts"/>

