|}

The first major athletic event held at the stadium was the Vaux Breweries International Athletics meet in July 1961. According to its sponsors, the highlight of this meet was the team three-mile race, won by the Blackpool and Fylde Athletic club who were awarded a gold tankard as their prize.<ref name="BGR"/> Attracted by a prize fund of <U+00A3>500 and the imminent  [[AAA Championships]] in London, the event attracted several athletes from New Zealand, including [[Athletics at the 1960 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 5000 metres|reigning 5000m metre Olympic champion]] [[Murray Halberg]] and [[Peter Snell]], the [[Athletics at the 1960 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 800 metres|reigning 800m Olympic champion]].<ref name="McGuirk"/> Watched by a capacity crowd of 10,000 spectators, the men won their respective races; Halberg placed first in the [[Mile run|mile]] with a time of 4:03:70 and Snell led a [[New Zealand]] one-two in the 880 yard event, finishing ahead of teammate Gary Philpott in 1:50:40.<ref name="McGuirk"/>

When the comprehensive refurbishment of the stadium was completed more than a decade later, Brendan Foster (by this time a Gateshead Council employee) proposed an international athletics meet. On 3 August 1974, the first "Gateshead Games" were staged in front of around 10,000 spectators.<ref name="Gibson 2004:1"/><ref name="UKA"/> Four weeks before he won the European 3000m title at the [[1974 European Athletics Championships]] in [[Rome]], Foster kept his earlier promise to run in the men's 3000m and won the race in a new world-record time of 7:35:20. According to journalist John Gibson, Foster's performance gave the meet, broadcast live by [[Tyne Tees Television]], "landmark status".<ref name="Gibson 2004:1"/><ref name="UKA"/> A plaque commemorating the record was later placed at the entrance to the stadium.<ref name="ICN"/>

The Gateshead Games became an annual event, which gave the stadium credibility as a major sporting venue.<ref name="ICN"/><ref name="Gibson 2004:1"/> In his managerial capacity with Gateshead Council, Foster was increasingly able to attract athletes to the games. In 1977, Foster had to intervene when [[BBC Radio Newcastle]] provided the wrong [[Ethiopian national anthem]] which, when played, offended [[Miruts Yifter]] sufficiently that he and his teammates started off towards [[Newcastle International Airport]]. The intervention worked<U+2014>in the end, Foster asked Yifter and his teammates if they would sing the anthem themselves, which they did in the middle of the stadium<U+2014>and Yifter returned to outclass a field including [[Steve Ovett]] over 5000m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html|title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster|first=John|last=Gibson|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2004|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.3</ref> The track was resurfaced by Regisport in 1982<ref name="TrackDir">{{cite web|url=http://www.runtrackdir.com/details.asp?track=gateshead&country=uk|title=Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Running Track Directory|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=30 August 2012}} This site is a redirect from the UK Athletics website.</ref> and the venues' profile was further raised in the summer of 1983, when Gateshead-born athlete [[Steve Cram]]{{refn|group=nb|UK Athletics state that Cram was born in Gateshead,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/e-inspire/hall-of-fame-athletes/steve-cram/|title=Hall of Fame Athletes &ndash; Steve Cram|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|year=2012|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref> as does an interview with Cram by ''Track and Field News'' in September 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/archive/Interviews/Steve%20Cram.pdf|title=T & F N &ndash; Interview, Steve Cram|work=Track and Field News|first=Steve|last=Powell|date=12 September 1985|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref> Other sources, including an article from the [[University of Sunderland]] website, claim he was born in [[Jarrow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://services.sunderland.ac.uk/universitysport/newsevents/news/news/index.php?nid=500|title=News Story &ndash; Steve Cram named new Chancellor|publisher=[[University of Sunderland]]|date=23 May 2008|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref>}} faced Sebastian Coe over 800m in the Gateshead Games. In front of a reported crowd of 15,000 who were "shoehorned into the bowl" and millions more watching on BBC's [[Sunday Grandstand]], Cram prevailed to spark "pandemonium" in his final race before winning the gold medal at the [[1983 World Championships in Athletics|1983 World Athletics Championships]] in [[Helsinki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_headline=face-to-face-steve-cram%26method=full%26objectid=17020775%26page=1%26siteid=50081-name_page.html|title=Face to Face: Steve Cram|first=John|last=Gibson|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=2 May 2006|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref>

In 1989, Gateshead hosted the [[1989 European Cup (athletics)|Europa Cup]]. The men's competition was won for the first time by a Great Britain team captained by [[Linford Christie]] and which included [[Kriss Akabusi]] and [[Jack Buckner]]; the event was described a decade later as having had an "invigorating effect" on those who were in attendance.<ref name="Europa1"/> Four years later, on 30 July 1993, a stadium-record crowd of 14,797<ref name="McGuirk"/> watched Christie, by this time [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 100 metres|the reigning 100m Olympic champion]], in action again &ndash; this time against his old rival [[Carl Lewis]] in a race where both men were reportedly paid <U+00A3>100,000 irrespective of the result.<ref name="Rowbottom">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/athletics-climate-and-form-point-to-a-christie-victory-world-and-olympic-champions-play-down-the-implications-of-tonights-gateshead-showdown-for-world-championships-in-stuttgart-1488119.html|title=Athletics: Climate and form point to a Christie victory: World and Olympic champions play down the implications of tonight's Gateshead showdown for World Championships in Stuttgart|first=Mike|last=Rowbottom|work=[[The Independent]]|date=30 July 1993|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> Christie won in a time of 10.07 seconds, ahead of [[Jon Drummond]] in second and Lewis, who finished "a distant third".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/jamaican-sprinters-yohan-blake-and-usain-bolt-refuse-to-race-headtohead-8092692.html|title=Jamaican sprinters Yohan Blake and Usain Bolt refuse to race head-to-head |first=Simon|last=Turnbull|work=[[The Independent]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> The 100m race was the highlight of the "high profile" Vauxhall Invitational meet, which was televised in the UK by [[ITV]] and watched by around 10 million viewers. [[Michael Johnson (sprinter)|Michael Johnson]], [[John Regis (athlete)|John Regis]] and Steve Cram competed in various events at the Vauxhall Invitational.<ref name="Rowbottom"/>

In August 1998, Gateshead was selected to host the [[2000 European Cup (athletics)|2000 Europa Cup]] after the [[European Athletic Association]] switched the event from original host venue [[Martinique]] to avoid athletes travelling long distances in an Olympic year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/athletics-gatesheads-european-cup-1173824.html|title=Athletics: Gateshead's European Cup|work=[[The Independent]]|date=24 August 1998|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> This made Gateshead the first venue to host the event twice.<ref name="Diamond">{{cite web|url=http://www.diamondleague.com/News/News-Archive/An-athletics-snapshot-of-GATESHEAD/|title=An athletic snapshot of Gateshead|first=David|last=Powell|publisher=Diamond League.com|date=20 November 2009|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> On 16&ndash;17 July 2000, spectators at Gateshead once again saw Great Britain's men's team take the title, this time by half a point from Germany in second place; the British victory came despite missing ten first-choice team members. The women's event was won by Russia, who defeated second-placed Germany by thirteen points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/4759741/European-Cup-Athletics-Relay-squad-find-Britains-winning-kick.html|title=European Cup Athletics: Relay squad find Britain's winning kick|first=Brendan|last=Gallagher|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 July 2000|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Paula Radcliffe 2005.jpg|right|upright|border|thumb|[[Paula Radcliffe]] runs the 10,000m at Gateshead in 2004]]Foster's "Gateshead Games" had become the [[British Grand Prix (athletics)|British Grand Prix]] by 2003, and on 13 July 21-year-old [[Yelena Isinbayeva]] set a [[Women's pole vault world record progression|new world record]] of 4.82m in the women's [[pole vault]] event. Isinbayeva's achievement in the last event of the meet was so unexpected that only 1,000 of the 10,000 spectators witnessed it, the rest having left early. For her achievement, she was given a bonus cheque for $50,000.<ref name="autogenerated2003"/> On 27 June 2004, Isinbayeva returned to Gateshead. This time the event organisers decided to schedule the pole vault event earlier and were rewarded when Isinbayeva defied extremely windy conditions to post a new record mark of 4.87m.<ref name="IAAF"/> Isinbayeva was the second woman to set a world record in the pole vault at Gateshead; [[Daniela Bartova]] did so in 1995.<ref name="Diamond"/> In 2006, a crowd of 8,500 saw [[Asafa Powell]] equal the world record of 9.77 seconds in the [[100 metres|men's 100m]]. The official, un-rounded time of 9.762 seconds was then the fastest time ever recorded. The meet was also notable for the return to competition of [[Dwain Chambers]] after his ban for using [[Tetrahydrogestrinone|performance enhancing drugs]], and for [[Eliud Kipchoge]] breaking Foster's stadium record over 3000m that had stood for more than three decades.<ref name="rowbottom2006"/>

In 2010, the British Grand Prix at Gateshead was chosen as one of the inaugural fourteen [[IAAF Diamond League 2010|Diamond League]] events,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/media/news/news-archive-pre-2011/april-2010/30-04-10-gay/|title=Diamond League|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=30 April 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> but although competitors included [[Tyson Gay]], Powell, [[Jessica Ennis]] and [[Vincent Chepkok]], the attendance was unusually poor, causing the local press to wonder whether Gateshead's contract for the marquee event would be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/newcastle-sports/newcastle-sports/athletics-news/2010/07/12/tyson-gay-beats-asafa-powell-at-gateshead-stadium-61634-26831826/|title=Tyson Gay beats Asafa Powell at Gateshead Stadium|first=Stuart|last=Rayner|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> Those fears were to prove well-founded when [[UK Athletics]] agreed to a three-year contract to stage the event at the [[Alexander Stadium]] in [[Birmingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/media/news/news-archive-pre-2011/november-2010/22-11-10-aviva-birmingham-grand-prix/|title=aviva birmingham grand prix|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=22 November 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> The move prompted one reporter to lament that "the switch is a major blow to both Gateshead International Stadium and North-East sport in general, but can hardly be regarded as a major surprise given the dwindling support for major athletics events in the region."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/8679464.North_East_athletics_loses_its_flagship_event/|title=North-East athletics loses its flagship event|first=Scott|last=Wilson|work=[[The Northern Echo]]|date=21 November 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> This loss was mitigated somewhat by the European Athletic Association's decision to award Gateshead the [[2013 European Team Championships]], the successor to the Europa Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.european-athletics.org/index.php?option=com_content&catid=1&id=10030&view=article|title=Gateshead to host 2013 European Athletics Team Championships|publisher=[[European Athletics Association]]|date=June 2011|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> In doing so, Gateshead will become the only stadium to host the European Team Championships on three occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/gateshead-awarded-2013-european-team-championships/|title=Gateshead awarded 2013 European Team Championships|work=[[Athletics Weekly]]|date=6 June 2011|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>

==Tenants==

===Gateshead Senators===
{{main|Gateshead Senators}}
The [[Gateshead Senators]] (originally the Gateshead International Senators) are an [[American football]] club formed in 1988 when the Newcastle Senators, who played at at Northern Rugby Club, moved across the Tyne to play at the Gateshead International Stadium.<ref name="SenHistory">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-senators.com/history.html|title=Gateshead Senators &ndash; History|publisher=Gateshead&ndash;Senators.com|year=2012|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> The club has had mixed fortunes but their most successful season came in 1999. Having won eight of their nine games in the regular season, the team won the Division One North title and advanced to the end-of-season playoffs. After beating the Merseyside Nighthawks 43&ndash;0 in the quarter-finals, the Senators defeated the [[Essex Spartans]] 33&ndash;19 in the semi-finals to reach the championship final. At the [[Saffron Lane sports centre|Saffron Lane Stadium]] in [[Leicester]], the Senators faced the [[Bristol Aztecs (American football)|Bristol Aztecs]]. In a tight encounter, the Senators claimed the Division One [[British American Football League]] title with a 7&ndash;2 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.users.zetnet.co.uk/pcrrn/senators/final99.htm|title=Gateshead Senators Division One Champions|publisher=[[Gateshead Senators]]|year=1999|accessdate=17 November 2012}} This site is a redirect from the official history links provided on the Gateshead Senators website.</ref> The club reached the playoffs again in the next three seasons but were unable to replicate that success, and after a season voluntarily spent in Division Two in 2003, returned to Division One North in 2004. They continue to play in that division, and in the 2012 season failed to make the playoffs after recording five wins and five defeats in their ten games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafanl.co.uk/team/18|title=Gateshead Senators|publisher=[[BAFA National Leagues|British American Football National League]]|year=2012|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref>

The Senators were a tenant at Gateshead Stadium from 1988 to 2011.<ref name="SenHistory"/> In 2012, the club announced plans to move away from Gateshead for the start of the 2012 season to create "a better game-day experience" and they now play at the [[Monkton Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Grounds+for+optimism+over+Senators%27+switch%3B+AMERICAN+FOOTBALL.-a0277972301|title=Grounds for optimism over Senators switch|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref>

===Gateshead Football Club===
{{main|Gateshead F.C.}}
The original [[Gateshead F.C.|Gateshead football club]] played in [[The Football League]], reached the quarter-finals of the [[FA Cup]] in 1953 and played their home games at [[Redheugh Park]]. In 1960, the Football League failed to re-elect the club and after several years playing in local leagues, the club folded in 1973. They was soon replaced by Gateshead United, a new club formed when South Shields F.C. moved from Simonside to play in Gateshead in 1974. That club folded in 1977 but was replaced by the present Gateshead F.C.<ref name="GFC history">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/club-history|title=The history of Gateshead Football Club|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|year=2012|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref>

Gateshead United played at Gateshead Stadium from their inception, and the present team have been tenants since their formation in 1977.<ref name="GFC history"/> In May 2008 Gateshead hosted [[Buxton F.C.|Buxton]] in a promotion play-off and won 2&ndash;0 in front of 1,402 spectators, the largest crowd to watch the club at the ground in 14 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bogie%27s+over+the+Toon+with+victory%3B+Gateshead+clinch+promotion+with...-a0178633259|title=Bogie's over the Toon with victory|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=5 May 2008|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> That record was broken a year later when 4,121 saw Gateshead defeat [[A.F.C. Telford United|AFC Telford United]] 2&ndash;0 on 9 May 2009 to win promotion to the [[Conference National]] league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2282/gateshead-1-0-afc-telford-united|title=Gateshead 1&ndash;0 AFC Telford United|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|date=10 May 2009|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> The current record attendance for a competitive fixture stands at 5,156, set in March 2011 when Gateshead played host to [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] in the second leg of the [[FA Trophy]] semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/3330/gateshead-0-0-darlington|title=Gateshead 0&ndash;0 Darlington|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|date=20 March 2011|accessdate=16 February 2013}}</ref> Gateshead F.C. continue to play at Gateshead Stadium but, according to North East Life magazine, it is "a fine but inappropriate stadium&nbsp;... as a football ground it can be a soulless home".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://northeast.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/gateshead-fc-dare-to-dream-37130/|title=Gateshead FC dare to dream|publisher=North East Life|year=2012|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> In 2009, chairman Graham Wood unveiled plans to move to a [[Gateshead F.C. new stadium|new, purpose-built 9,000 capacity ground]] on Prince Consort Road in the centre of Gateshead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/8330448.stm|title=Football stadium plans unveiled|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=28 October 2009|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> Detailed proposals were published soon after,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/new-stadium|title=Gateshead's New Stadium|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|year=2009|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> and Wood told local media in 2012 that  he expects the move to increase crowds and alleviate the financial constraints on him as he continues to bankroll the club; it is estimated that crowds would need to reach 3,000 regularly for the club to operate profitably from Gateshead Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/non-league-football/2012/08/23/grounds-for-hope-over-new-gateshead-fc-stadium-72703-31679339/|title=Grounds for hope over new Gateshead FC stadium|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|first=Steve|last=Brown|date=23 August 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref> According to the original proposal, the stadium was expected to be ready for the 2012&ndash;13 season, but financing has been difficult and the proposed move is now scheduled to take place in August 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/non-league-football/2011/06/06/optimism-over-gateshead-s-new-stadium-plans-72703-28827957/|title=Optimism over Gateshead's new stadium plans|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=6 June 2011|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2012/10/09/athletes-forced-to-make-way-for-footballers-at-gateshead-stadium-61634-31994732/|title=Athletes forced to make way for footballers at Gateshead Stadium|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|first=Michael|last=Brown|date=9 October 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref>

===Gateshead Harriers===

[[Gateshead Harriers]] are an athletic club based at Gateshead International Stadium. Founded in 1904 as Gateshead St Mary's Church Running Club, they were initially a men-only club until allowing the admission of women in 1951. The club moved to the Gateshead Youth Stadium in 1956, making the Harriers the stadium's oldest tenant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-harriers.co.uk/home/|title=Welcome to Gateshead Harriers|publisher=Gateshead Harriers|year=2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> In 2006 they won promotion to the first division of the [[British Athletics League]] and were the only club from the north-east of England to compete at that level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=17031761%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=harriers-join-big-league-name_page.html|title=Harriers join big league|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2006|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> After a six-year stay in the division, the Harriers were relegated to division two in August 2012 after failing to win enough points at the final meet of the season at Eton to prevent a bottom-two league finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2012/08/20/battling-gateshead-harriers-fail-to-beat-relegation-72703-31656928/|title=Battling Gateshead Harriers fail to beat relegation|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=22 August 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Club officials received over 100 new applications for membership in the aftermath of [[2012 Olympics|the 2012 London Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2012/08/30/london-2012-olympics-legacy-is-up-and-running-72703-31725773/|title=London 2012 Olympics legacy is up and running|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref>

At least one Gateshead Harrier has taken part in every [[Olympic Games|Olympics]] and [[Paralympic Games|Paralympics]] held since 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/People%20and%20Living/award/award.aspx|title=The Gateshead Award|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Notable alumni include Brendan Foster, who joined the club aged 17 and later claimed that "my first aim was to be the best runner of Gateshead Harriers".<ref>Luhtala, 2002: 94</ref> Foster, inducted into the [[England Athletics Hall of Fame]] in 2010 and recently voted the eleventh "greatest [[Geordie]]" in a local poll, later became the president of Gateshead Harriers and remains so as of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2010/11/04/brendan-foster-inducted-into-hall-of-fame-72703-27599438/|title=Brendan Foster inducted into Hall of Fame|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 November 2010|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/08/28/chronicle-s-100-greatest-geordies-no-s-12-to-10-72703-31711383/2/|title=Chronicle's 100 Greatest Geordies, Nos 10&ndash;12|first=Michael|last=Kelly|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=28 August 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Current world triple-jump record holder [[Jonathan Edwards (athlete)|Jonathan Edwards]], another member of the England Athletics Hall of Fame,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandathletics.org/page.asp?section=847&sectionTitle=Hall+of+Fame+2009+inductees|title=Hall of Fame &ndash; Inductees 2009|publisher=[[England Athletics Hall of Fame]]|year=2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> joined Gateshead Harriers in 1991. Edwards was a member of the club when he set his record mark in [[1995 World Championships in Athletics <U+2013> Men's triple jump|winning gold]] at the [[1995 World Championships in Athletics|1995 World Championships]] in [[Helsinki]], when winning [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's triple jump|Olympic gold]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Games]] and a [[2001 World Championships in Athletics <U+2013> Men's triple jump|second world title]] a year later in [[Edmonton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1477695.stm|title=North east toasts hero Edwards|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=7 August 2001|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Both Foster and Edwards are honourary life members of the club.<ref>Miller, 2008: 173</ref>

===Gateshead Thunder===
{{main|Gateshead Thunder}}
[[File:Gateshead vs limoux.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Gateshead Thunder]] playing against Limoux in the [[Challenge Cup]] at Gateshead International Stadium in 2004]]In 1998, Gateshead was awarded a [[rugby league]] franchise after a three-way contest with Cardiff and Swansea. The result was Gateshead Thunder, who played in [[Super League IV]] in 1999.<ref name="OFT">{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=940|title=Club History &ndash; Super League|publisher=Gateshead Thunder|year=2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> The Thunder played at Gateshead International Stadium and the club had, according to sports journalist Andy Wilson, "an enjoyable and surprisingly successful season" which included home and away wins against [[St Helens RLFC|St Helens]] and a sixth place finish in the table &ndash; missing out on the playoffs by two points.<ref name="Guard">{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2009/may/29/rugby-league-challenge-cup-gateshead|title=Gateshead Thunder are ready to make a big noise against St Helens|first=Andy|last=Wilson|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Despite these performances, which attracted an average crowd of 3,895 to Gateshead Stadium, the franchise lost <U+00A3>700,000 in its first year<ref name="OFT"/> and in November 1999 the [[Rugby Football League]] (RFL) approved a merger with the Hull Sharks.<ref name="bbcrfl">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/rugby_league/521562.stm|title=Rugby League League's northern empire cut back|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=19 November 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> The result was the formation of [[Hull F.C.]], and when the authorities refused permission for the merged clubs to enter a Hull-based team into the RFL's [[Rugby Football League Championship Second Division|second tier]],<ref name="OFT"/> the franchise moved almost in its entirety to Hull, ending Gateshead's Super League participation after a single season; according to Wilson, the Thunder was "left to die, provoking bitter resentment" from supporters.<ref name="Guard"/>

According to journalist Richard Bott, since the demise of the original Thunder side the club has "struggled for their very existence."<ref name="mail">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-1189626/Thorman-keeps-family-Gateshead-skipper-looks-forward-giant-Cup-clash.html|title=Thorman keeps it in the family as Gateshead skipper looks forward to giant Cup clash|first=Richard|last=Bott|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=29 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> There have been some highlights, including winning [[Championship 1]] in 2008<ref name="OFT"/> and a run to the quarter-final of the [[Challenge Cup]] in 2009 which ended in a 66&ndash;6 defeat to Super League side St Helens in front of 4,325 fans at Gateshead International Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-1189815/Gateshead-6-St-Helens-66-Saints-march-fourth-Wembley.html|title=Gateshead 6 St Helens 66: Saints march fourth towards Wembley|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=30 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> However, the Thunder went through a 64-game losing streak spanning two-and-a-half years before winning against [[Workington Town]] on 29 August 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/rugby-news/gateshead-thunder/2012/08/30/gateshead-thunder-in-shock-victory-over-visitors-72703-31725698/|title=Gateshead Thunder in shock victory over visitors|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> The club is now in its fourth incarnation.<ref name="OFT"/> Relations between the Thunder and Gateshead Council have been strained at times, with a possible move to [[Kingston Park (stadium)|Kingston Park]] mooted, and ultimately rejected, in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/sport/rugby-north-east/2006/05/10/sights-set-on-top-flight-79310-17055903/|title=Sights set on top flight|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|work=[[Sunday Sun|The Sunday Sun]]|date=10 May 2006|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> In 2008, the club committed itself again to Gateshead Stadium for the immediate future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/2008/10/30/thunder-agree-deal-to-continue-playing-at-stadium-72703-22150967/|title=Thunder agree deal to continue playing at Stadium|first=Nick|last=Purewal|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=30 October 2008|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref>

==Concert venue==

Gateshead International Stadium has been used for many years as a concert venue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gebrselassie set to star at Gateshead|first=Alan|last=Pattullo|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=2 June 1999|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> On 31 July 1982, [[The Police]] performed at the stadium as part of their [[Ghost in the Machine Tour]], with [[U2]] as a supporting act. Reports in the local press suggested that The Police seemed disappointed that the stadium was only half full and cited high ticket prices and poor weather as possible causes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lukewarm greeting as hero returns|first=Bill|last=Brown|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|date=1 August 1982|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> On 16 June 1992 [[Guns N' Roses]], supported by [[Soundgarden]] and [[Faith No More]], performed at the stadium. This time the weather was hot and sunny which helped ensure that the concert, part of the [[Use Your Illusion Tour]], was a sell-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/2012/05/11/interview-dizzy-reed-ahead-of-guns-n-roses-gig-72703-30948744/|title=Interview: Dizzy Reed ahead of Guns N' Roses gig|first=Mick|last=Burgess|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=11 May 2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> American [[rock group]] [[Bon Jovi]] have played twice at the stadium. The first occasion was on 27 June 1995, while supported by [[Skin (British band)|Skin]], on their [[These Days Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/multimedia/entertainment/2012/10/30/flashback-bon-jovi-play-the-gateshead-stadium-72703-32129039/#2|title=Flashback: Bon Jovi play the Gateshead Stadium|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=30 October 2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skinfreak.co.uk/biography|title=Biography|publisher=Skin: The Official Website|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> The group returned to Gateshead on 22 August 2000 as part of their [[Crush Tour]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/893047.stm|title=Bon Jovi delights British fans|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=23 August 2000|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Another artist who has performed multiple times at Gateshead International Stadium is [[Tina Turner]]. As part of her [[Foreign Affair: The Farewell Tour]], Turner performed twice on consecutive nights (21&ndash;22 July 1990) and attracted a total of 60,000 spectators.<ref>Welch, 1995: 192</ref> Turner performed for a third time at the stadium as part of her [[Wildest Dreams Tour]] on 12 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/TINA.-a061156467|title=Tina|first=Lisa|last=Burrows|work=[[The People]]|date=26 May 1996|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> Other artists to have played at the stadium include [[Bryan Adams]], [[Rod Stewart]] and [[Simple Minds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2003/01/27/a-billion-fans-bowl-star-over-72703-12575156/|title=A billion fans bowl over star|first=Sonia|last=Sharma|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=27 January 2003|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>

==Transport==

[[File:Gateshead Stadium Metro Station - geograph.org.uk - 70792.jpg|thumb|[[Gateshead Stadium Metro station]]]]
Gateshead International Stadium is {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} east of Gateshead Town Centre and is on the [[A184 road (England)#Triple-digit roads|A184 Felling Bypass]], with access to a car park at Neilson Road.<ref>Powell, 2010: 7 at para.15</ref> Journey time by car from Gateshead town centre is approximately five minutes and a further five minutes travel from Newcastle upon Tyne.<ref>Using Gateshead International Stadium as reference points. See {{cite web|url=http://www.simplygo.com/download/publication/42497.52|title=The Loop: Timetable|publisher=[[Go North East]]|date=29 July 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> A footpath runs adjacent to the Felling bypass and the journey by foot from Gateshead town centre takes some fifteen minutes. A journey east to [[Heworth Interchange]] also takes around fifteen minutes. Two designated cycle routes run past the stadium. These are [[National Cycle Route 72|Hadrian's Way]], which provides access from [[Tynemouth]] in the east and [[Wylam]] in the west, and the [[National Cycle Route 14|Keelman's Way]], which runs along the south bank of the [[River Tyne]] towards [[Blaydon-on-Tyne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.ac.uk/media/15274/academy_for_sport_travel_guide.pdf|title=How to get to the Academy for Sport at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[Gateshead College]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}} at p.1</ref>

The stadium is well served by public transport. It has its own [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] station, the [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station]]. This is at Shelley Drive, some five minutes' walk from the ground.<ref name="sport2">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.ac.uk/media/15274/academy_for_sport_travel_guide.pdf|title=How to get to the Academy for Sport at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[Gateshead College]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}} at p.2</ref> Trains run direct from this station to all other Metro destinations; trains to [[South Shields Metro station|South Shields]] and [[South Hylton metro station|South Hylton]] stop at platform one while trains travelling towards [[St James Metro station|St James]] and [[Airport Metro station (Tyne and Wear)|Airport]] stop at platform two.<ref name="metro">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/timetables/gateshead-stadium|title=Metro Stations: Gateshead Stadium|publisher=[[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive]]|date=July 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> The Gateshead Stadium Metro station is open seven days a week<ref name="metro"/> and at peak times seventeen trains per hour stop there.<ref name="sport2"/> The nearest mainline railway station is [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle Central Station]], around {{convert|3|mi|km|0}} away, though local rail travel calls at Heworth Interchange.<ref name="sport2"/> [[Go North East]] operate the 93/4 "Loop" bus service, which provides access to the stadium from the [[Team Valley]], [[Gateshead Interchange]], Heworth Interchange and [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Gateshead|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]] in [[Sheriff Hill]]. This bus runs every fifteen minutes during the day and every half-hour during evenings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simplygo.com/download/publication/5870.28|title=Route Map: Loop|publisher=[[Go North East]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref>

